2025-04-15T21:07:36.732119Z assistant

Yo. That SSH key "gaslight" effect is way too real sometimes. Here's whats likely going on and how to slay it cleanly so GitHub CLI stops playing games.

TL;DR Why Its Failing

You're authenticated via gh CLI and your SSH key exists but Git itself can't use that SSH key to connect.
So GitHub CLI says, Youre logged in,
but Git says, Nope, not you.

Root Issues (and How to Fix 'Em)

1. SSH key mismatch or config misdirection

You have a key (like id_rsa_ring_github) but Git might not be using it unless explicitly told to.

2. Your SSH config file may not be set to use that key

Even if it exists, Git doesnt automatically know which key to use.

SOLUTION: Setup Your ~/.ssh/config

Run:

nano ~/.ssh/config

Then add this block:

Host github.com
  HostName github.com
  User git
  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa_ring_github
  IdentitiesOnly yes

IdentityFile must point to your private key, not the .pub.

Then make sure your permissions are tight:

chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa_ring_github
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_rsa_ring_github.pub
chmod 700 ~/.ssh

3. Test SSH connection

Run:

ssh -T git@github.com

You should see:

Hi HawkEyeTheRapper! You've successfully authenticated...

If not SSH is still blind to your key. Double-check the config path + permissions.

Bonus Debug Commands

ssh-add -l                 # List keys in ssh-agent
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa_ring_github  # Add the key explicitly if missing

Or if your agent is off:

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa_ring_github

Final Check: GitHub Account Key

Go to GitHub Settings SSH and GPG keys
Make sure the public key there matches the one you just set (.pub file).

If you ever have two keys using the same public key, GitHub will 422 you like:

key is already in use
That's fine it just means its already linked to your account.

After all that:

Try cloning again:

gh repo clone HawkEyeTheRapper/hawkeyeastro
